    <introduction>
        <p>We learned how to solve a system of linear equations by substitution. In this section, we will learn a second algebraic method for solving systems of linear equations.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="ova8GSmPV4o"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Systems of Equations by Elimination</title>

        <example xml:id="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro">
        <p>Michelle wants to invest <dollar/><m>10{,}000</m> in two accounts. She would like to put <dollar/><m>1{,}200</m> more in Account A than Account B. How much money should she invest in each account?</p>

        <p>Assume Michelle will invest <m>x</m> dollars in Account A, and <m>y</m> dollars in Account B. Based on the given conditions, we can write the following system of equations:<md>
            <mrow>
                \left\{
                    \begin{alignedat}{4}
                    x \amp {}+{} \amp  y \amp {}={} \amp 10000 \\
                    x \amp {}-{} \amp  y \amp {}={} \amp 1200 \\
                    \end{alignedat}
                \right.
            </mrow></md></p>

        <p>We could solve this system by substitution as we learned in the last section, but there is an easier method. First, we need to learn a new property.</p>

         <p>If we have two equations, we can add them together to create a new equation. For example:<md>
            <mrow>1+5\amp=6</mrow>
            <mrow>3+8\amp=11</mrow>
            <mrow>1+5+3+8\amp=6+11</mrow>
        </md>Since the two original equations are true, the new equation is also true. Similarly, let's add each side of the two equations for the scenario:<md>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>x-y\amp=1200</mrow>
            <intertext>Adding each side of the two equations:</intertext>
            <mrow>x+x+y-y\amp=11200</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=11200</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=5600</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>To finish solving this system of equations, we need the value of <m>y</m>. We will find it like we did in the substitution method, by replacing <m>x</m> with <m>5600</m> in either equation. We will choose the first equation:<md>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=4400</mrow>
        </md>To check the solution, we need to substitute <m>x=5600</m> and <m>y=4400</m> in each equation:<md>
            <mrow>x-y\amp=1200</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}-\substitute{4400}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1200</mrow>
            <mrow>1200\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}1200</mrow>
            <intertext>and</intertext>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}+\substitute{4400}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}10000</mrow>
            <mrow>10000\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}10000</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>We have verified that our solution is correct. In summary, Michelle should invest <dollar/><m>5{,}600</m> in Account A, and <dollar/><m>4{,}400</m> in Account B.</p>
        </example>

        <remark><p>This method works in <xref ref="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro">Example</xref> because <m>y</m> and <m>-y</m> cancel after we add each side of the two equations. Once the <m>y</m> terms were eliminated we were able to solve for <m>x</m>. This method is called the <term>elimination method</term>. Some textbooks call this method the <term>addition method</term>, because we added the sides of two equations to eliminate a variable.</p>
    
        <p>If neither variable will immediately cancel, we can still use this method but it will require that we first adjust one of the equations.</p>
        </remark>

        <p> Let's look at another example with a more complicated system of equations, where one variable won't immediately be eliminated when the equations are added.</p>


        <example xml:id="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro-build-one-equation">
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations below using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            3x \amp {}-{} \amp  4y \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\
                            5x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 18 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To start, we want to see whether it will be easier to eliminate <m>x</m> or <m>y</m>. We see that the coefficients of <m>x</m> in each equation are <m>3</m> and <m>5</m>, and the coefficients of <m>y</m> are <m>-4</m> and <m>8</m>. Because <m>8</m> is a multiple of <m>4</m> and the coefficients already have opposite signs, the <m>y</m> variable will be easier to eliminate.
                </p>

                <p>To eliminate the <m>y</m> terms, we will multiply each side of the first equation by <m>2</m> so that <m>-8y</m> and <m>8y</m> will cancel:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}(3x-4y)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>6x-8y\amp=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We now have an equivalent system of equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                6x \amp {}-{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\
                                5x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 18 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Next, adding the left and right sides of the equations, we get:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6x+5x\amp=4+18</mrow>
                        <mrow>11x\amp=22</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    To solve for <m>y</m>, we will substitute <m>2</m> for <m>x</m> into either of the original equations or the new one. We will use the original first equation, <m>3x-4y=2</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>3(\substitute{2})-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>6-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>-4y\amp=-4</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=1</mrow>
                    </md>

                    Our solution is <m>x=2</m> and <m>y=1</m>. We will check this in both of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5x+8y\amp=18</mrow>
                        <mrow>5(\substitute{2})+8(\substitute{1})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}18</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+8\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}18</mrow>
                        <intertext>and</intertext>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>3(\substitute{2})-4(\substitute{1})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}2</mrow>
                        <mrow>6-4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The solution to this system is <m>(2,1)</m> and the solution set is <m>\{(2,1)\}</m>. 
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Alicia wants to consume <m>600</m> calories and <m>20</m> grams of fat for breakfast. A small avocado contains <m>300</m> calories and <m>30</m> grams of fat. Her bagels contain <m>400</m> calories and <m>8</m> grams of fat. Write and solve a system of equations to determine how many bagels and avocados she should eat.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To write this system of equations, we first need to define our variables. Let <m>A</m> be the number of avocados consumed and let <m>B</m> be the number of bagels consumed. In our first equation, we will add the number of calories in the avocados and bagels:
                    <me>300A+400B=600</me>
                Similarly, in our second equation, we will add the grams of fat:
                    <me>30A+8B=20</me>
                Our system of equations looks like this:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                300A \amp {}+{} \amp  400B \amp {}={} \amp 600 \\
                                30A \amp {}+{} \amp  8B \amp {}={} \amp 20 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
<!--                <p>The two methods we've studied so far to solve this system of equations (graphing and substitution) would both be challenging here. We're going to use a third method, known as the <term>elimination method</term>. This method will involve building one of the equations so that it has a variable term that is the opposite of the variable term in the other equation. Once these opposites are present, we can add each side of the two equations to obtain a new equation where one variable is <em>eliminated</em>.</p>
-->              <p>Looking at the terms <m>300A</m> and <m>30A</m>, we can eliminate the
                 <m>A</m> variable if we multiply the second equation by <m>-10</m> to get <m>-300A</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 30A + 8B\amp=20</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{-10}(30A+8B)\amp=\multiplyleft{-10}(20)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-300A-80B\amp=-200</mrow>
                    </md>
                An equivalent system can now be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                300A \amp {}+{} \amp  400B \amp {}={} \amp 600 \\
                                -300A \amp {}-{} \amp  80B \amp {}={} \amp -200 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                When we add the two equations together we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B+(-300A)+(-80B)\amp=600+(-200)</mrow>
                        <mrow>320B\amp=400</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{320B}{320}\amp=\divideunder{400}{320}</mrow>
                        <mrow>B\amp=\frac{5}{4}</mrow>
                    </md>
                We now know that she can eat <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> bagels (or one and one-quarter bagels). To determine the number of avocados, we will replace <m>B</m> with <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> in either of our equations. We will use the first one:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+400\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+500\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+500\subtractright{500}\amp=600\subtractright{500}</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A\amp=100</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{300A}{300}\amp=\divideunder{100}{300}</mrow>
                        <mrow>A\amp=\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>To check this result, we'll replace <m>B</m> with <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> and <m>A</m> with <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> in each of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}\right)+400\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}600</mrow>
                        <mrow>100+500\amp={\checkmark}{=}600</mrow>
                        <intertext>and</intertext>
                        <mrow>30A+8B\amp=20</mrow>
                        <mrow>30\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}\right)+8\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}20</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+10\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}20</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>In summary, Alicia can eat <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> bagels and <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> of an avocado in order to consume exactly <m>600</m> calories and <m>20</m> grams of fat.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    
