            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To use the elimination method here, we will first re-write each equation in standard form. This will involve putting all terms containing <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> on the left side and putting all constants on the right. After this, we will eliminate any denominators by multiplying each side by the LCD. For the first equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-\frac{y}{3}\amp=\frac{2}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>-\frac{y}{3}\subtractright{\frac{2}{15}x}\amp=\frac{2}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}\subtractright{\frac{2}{15}x}</mrow>
                        <mrow>-\frac{2}{15}x-\frac{y}{3}\amp=\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{15}\left(-\frac{2}{15}x-\frac{y}{3}\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{15}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-2x-5y\amp=3</mrow>
                    </md>
                For the second equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{2}x\amp=y-11</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{2}x\subtractright{y}\amp=y-11\subtractright{y}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{2}x-y\amp=-11</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}\left(\frac{5}{2}x-y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(-11)</mrow>
                        <mrow>5x-2y\amp=-22</mrow>
                    </md>
                Now the system of equations can be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                -2x \amp {}-{} \amp  5y \amp {}={} \amp 3 \\
                                5x \amp {}-{} \amp  2y \amp {}={} \amp -22 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                To eliminate <m>x</m> terms, we can multiply each side of the first equation by <m>5</m>, and multiply each side in the second equation by <m>2</m>. We have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                -10x \amp {}-{} \amp  25y \amp {}={} \amp 15 \\
                                10x \amp {}-{} \amp  4y \amp {}={} \amp -44 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        </mrow>
                        <intertext>Adding the left sides and right sides, of those two equations:</intertext>
                        <mrow>-10x-25y+10x-4y\amp=15+(-44)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-29y\amp=-29</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Substituting <m>y</m> with <m>1</m> into <m>-2x-5y=3</m>, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-2x-5y\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>-2x-5(\substitute{1})\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>-2x-5\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>-2x\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=-4</mrow>
                    </md>
                The solution is <m>(-4,1)</m>. Checking the solution is left as exercise.</p>
            </solution>
        </example> -->
    
    </subsection>
    
    <subsection>

        <title>Choosing Which Algebraic Method to Use</title>
            
            <p>You'll notice that in each of the examples above, both equations were in standard form (<m>Ax+By=C</m>). In that case it is usually easier to use the elimination method. If the equations are not in standard form, though, we may want to use substitution. Let's look at an example where we determine whether it will be simpler to use substitution or elimination.
            </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the method of your choice.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                    \left\{
                        \begin{alignedat}{3}
                        -\frac{1}{3}y\amp = \frac{1}{15}x + \frac{1}{5} \\
                        \frac{5}{2}x-y\amp = 6 \\
                        \end{alignedat}
                    \right.
                    </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First, we will remove the fractions by multiplying each equation by the LCD. For the first equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-\frac{1}{3}y\amp=\frac{1}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{15}\left(-\frac{1}{3}y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{15}\left(\frac{1}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-5y\amp=x+3</mrow>
                    </md>
                For the second equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{2}x-y\amp=6</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}\left(\frac{5}{2}x-y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(6)</mrow>
                        <mrow>5x-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                    </md>
                Now the system of equations can be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            -5y\amp=x+3 \\
                            5x-2y\amp=12 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                We could put the the first equation into standard form and use elimination. However, the <m>x</m>-variable in the first equation has a coefficient of one, so we will use the substitution method. Solving for <m>x</m> in the first equation we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            -5y\amp=x+3 \\
                            -5y\subtractright{3}\amp=x+3\subtractright{3}\ \\
                            -5y-3\amp=x \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        </mrow>
                        <intertext>Substituting <m>-5y-3</m> for <m>x</m> in the second equation we have:</intertext>
                        <mrow>5(\substitute{-5y-3})-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-25y-15-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-27y-15\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-27y\amp=27</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Substituting <m>-1</m> for <m>y</m>, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-5(\substitute{-1})-3\amp=x</mrow>
                        <mrow>5-3\amp=x</mrow>
                        <mrow>2\amp=x</mrow>
                    </md>
                The solution is <m>(2,-1)</m>. Checking the solution is left as an exercise.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark><p>To summarize, if a variable is already isolated or has a coefficient of one, consider using the substitution method. If both equations are in standard form or none of the coefficients are equal to one, we suggest using the elimination method.
        </p></remark>
    
    </subsection>

